{"title_page": "Bobby Rahal", "text_new": "{{short description|American racing driver}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name        = Bobby Rahal\n| image       = Bobby Rahal at the Barber Legends of Motorsport 2010.jpg\n| caption     = Rahal in 2010\n| nationality = {{flagicon|USA}} American\n| birth_name  = Robert Woodward Rahal\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1953|1|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Medina, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| titles      = 1986, 1987, 1992 [[PPG Indy Car World Series]] Champion<br>[[1986 Indianapolis 500]] Winner\n| awards      = \n| module1     =\n  {{Infobox Champ Car driver|child=yes\n  | years             = 1982\u20131998\n  | Total_Champ_Races = 266\n  | Years_In_Champ    = 18\n  | Champ_Car_Team    = Truesports (1982\u20131988)<br>Kraco (1989)<br>Galles-Kraco (1990\u20131991)<br>Rahal-Hogan (1992\u20131995)<br>Team Rahal (1996\u20131998)\n  | Best_Champ_Pos    = 1st \u2013 [[1986 IndyCar season|1986]], [[1987 IndyCar season|1987]], [[1992 IndyCar season|1992]]\n  | First_Champ_Race  = [[1982 Indianapolis 500]]\n  | Last_Champ_Race   = [[1998 CART season|1998]] [[Marlboro 500 (California)|Marlboro 500]] ([[California Speedway|Fontana]])\n  | First_Champ_Win   = [[1982 IndyCar season|1982]] [[Grand Prix of Cleveland|Budweiser Cleveland 500]] ([[Cleveland Burke Lakefront Airport|Cleveland]])\n  | Last_Champ_Win    = [[1992 IndyCar season|1992]] [[Bosch Spark Plug Grand Prix]] ([[Nazareth Speedway|Nazareth]])\n  | Champ_Wins        = 24\n  | Champ_Podiums     = 88\n  | Champ_Poles       = 17\n  }}\n| module2     =\n  {{Infobox F1 driver|child=yes\n  | name          = \n  | Years         = {{F1|1978}}\n  | Team(s)       =  [[Walter Wolf Racing|Wolf]]\n  | Races         = 2\n  | Championships = 0\n  | Wins          = 0\n  | Podiums       = 0\n  | Poles         = 0\n  | Points        = 0\n  | Fastest laps  = 0\n  | First race    = [[1978 United States Grand Prix]]\n  | First win     = \n  | Last win      = \n  | Last race     = [[1978 Canadian Grand Prix]]\n  }}\n| module3     =\n  {{Infobox NASCAR driver|child=yes\n  | name            = \n  | Total_Cup_Races = 1\n  | Years_In_Cup    = 1\n  | Cup_Car_Team    = \n  | Prev_Cup_Pos    = \n  | Previous_Year   = \n  | Best_Cup_Pos    = 91st \u2013 [[1984 NASCAR Winston Cup Series|1984]]\n  | First_Cup_Race  = [[1984 NASCAR Winston Cup Series|1984]] [[Winston Western 500]] ([[Riverside International Raceway|Riverside]])\n  | Last_Cup_Race   = \n  | First_Cup_Win   =\n  | Last_Cup_Win    =\n  | Cup_Wins        = 0\n  | Cup_Top_Tens    = 0\n  | Cup_Poles       = 0\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Woodward''' \"'''Bobby'''\" '''Rahal''' (born January 10, 1953) is an American former [[auto racing]] driver and team owner. As a driver he won three championships and 24 races in the [[Champ Car|CART]] open-wheel series, including the [[1986 Indianapolis 500]]. He also won the [[2004 Indianapolis 500]] as a team owner for the winning driver, [[Buddy Rice]].\n\nAfter retiring as a driver, Rahal held managerial positions with the [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]] Formula 1 team and also was an interim president of the CART series. Rahal was also a sports car driver during the 1980s, and made one NASCAR start for the Wood Brothers.\n\n==Racing career==\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = And it was frigid. A very cold day, and the race long \u2013 long for me. The longest I'd done before that was a 100-mile Formula Atlantic race, and this was a 200-mile grand prix. I just wanted to get to the end and get to the next race. It was a workman-like debut.\n |author = Rahal, speaking about his Formula One debut at [[Watkins Glen International|Watkins Glen]]<ref name=racer>{{cite web|last1=Pruett|first1=Marshall|title=Reflections: 1978 Formula 1 at Watkins Glen|url=http://www.racer.com/more/historic/item/124480-reflections-1978-formula-1-at-watkins-glen#!1978_F1_WatkinsGlen_MarshallPruettArchives_088a|website=racer.com|accessdate=13 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151213205114/http://www.racer.com/more/historic/item/124480-reflections-1978-formula-1-at-watkins-glen|archivedate=13 December 2015|date=11 December 2015}}</ref>\n |source = \n |width  = 20%\n |align  = left\n}}\nRahal began his career in SCCA feeder categories, eventually finishing second to [[Gilles Villeneuve]] in the [[1977 Formula Atlantic season|1977 Formula Atlantic championship]]. The following year, he competed in the [[1978 New Zealand Grand Prix]] with [[Fred Opert Racing]] ([[Formula Pacific]]) and in European [[Formula Three]] with [[Walter Wolf Racing|Wolf Racing]]. Near the end of the season, Rahal raced for the Wolf Formula 1 team in the [[1978 United States Grand Prix]] and the [[1978 Canadian Grand Prix]].<ref name=racer/> The deal with Wolf did not continue into the 1979 season, as Wolf signed up [[James Hunt]] for the one and only car available. Rahal began the 1979 racing a Chevron in [[Formula Two]], but returned to America mid-season and raced in the [[Can-Am]] series. During the next few seasons, he competed in various sports car events, including the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] and the [[IMSA GT Championship]].\n\nIn 1982, Rahal entered the [[Champ Car|CART]] series with the [[Truesports]] team, winning two races and finishing second in the championship behind [[Rick Mears]]. He continued racing for Truesports through the 1988 season, winning at least one race every year. In 1986, Rahal dramatically passed [[Kevin Cogan]] on a restart with two laps to go to win the [[1986 Indianapolis 500|Indianapolis 500]], only days before his team owner, [[Jim Trueman]] died of cancer. Later that year, Rahal won his first CART championship, and successfully defended it the following year.\n\nIn 1988, Rahal won the last race the [[Truesports]] team ever won, the [[Pocono 500 (Indycar)|Quaker State 500]] at Pocono, the only victory for the Judd engine ever.\n\nBy 1989, Rahal had ended his occasional forays into sports car racing and focused solely on CART. He moved over to the [[Kraco]] race team, but this association produced only two wins over three seasons.\n\nRahal competed in one NASCAR race in his career.  In November 1984 he drove the 7-11 sponsored Wood Brothers #21 Ford (substituting for Buddy Baker) to a 40th-place finish in the Winston Western 500 at Riverside International Speedway, completing only 44 laps before breaking a rear end gear.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.racing-reference.info/race/1984_Winston_Western_500/W |title=1984 Winston Western 500 |publisher=racing-reference.info |accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==IndyCar owner==\n[[File:Bobby-rahal mid-ohio 08-10-1996.jpg|thumb|left|Rahal driving for Team Rahal at Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course in 1996]]\nAfter losing the championship to [[Michael Andretti]] in [[1991 IndyCar season|1991]], Rahal (with partner Carl Hogan) acquired the assets to the former [[U.E. Patrick|Pat Patrick]] Racing team, with Rahal becoming an owner-driver. The team was an immediate success in [[1992 IndyCar season|1992]], producing four wins for Rahal and his third CART championship, making him the last owner-driver to win the CART title, and the last driver to win a race in his own car until [[Adrian Fernandez]] did so in [[2003 CART season|2003]]. In [[1993 IndyCar season|1993]], Rahal attempted to develop his own Rahal-Hogan chassis, but reverted to the [[Lola Racing Cars|Lola]] chassis after failing to qualify for the [[1993 Indianapolis 500]]. In [[1994 IndyCar season|1994]] the team brought the [[Honda]] engine into the CART series. Except for a second-place finish at [[1994 IndyCar season#Round Nine: Toronto|Toronto]], he and teammate [[Mike Groff]] struggled to show the full potential of an engine that would soon dominate the series. In [[1995 IndyCar season|1995]] at [[Long Beach Grand Prix|Long Beach]] Rahal became the 10th driver in [[American Championship Car Racing|Championship Car]] history (including [[American Automobile Association|AAA]], [[United States Auto Club|USAC]], and [[Champ Car|CART]]) to start 200 races in his career.<ref>[http://www.champcarstats.com/drivers/RahalBobby.htm ChampCarStats.com]</ref> Despite no wins, Rahal finished a strong 3rd in the 1995 standings using the [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]] engine.\n\nRahal continued as a racing driver until his retirement in [[1998 CART season|1998]]. Meanwhile, Hogan left to form his own team and [[Late Show with David Letterman|talk show host]] [[David Letterman]] became a minority owner in [[1996 IndyCar season|1996]]. The team became known as Team Rahal in 1996 and [[Rahal Letterman Racing]] in [[2004 IndyCar Series season|2004]], when Rahal switched from CART to the [[Indy Racing League|IRL]] full-time.\n\n==Other business roles==\nIn 2000, Rahal joined the [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]] Formula One team in a managerial capacity. During this time, Rahal attempted to hire championship-winning aerodynamicist [[Adrian Newey]], briefly believing that the deal had been completed, but was unsuccessful. However, Rahal was fired after reportedly attempting to sell driver [[Eddie Irvine]] to rivals [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]].<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://classic.autosport.com/news/atlasf1-report.php/id/5373/ | title = Lauda Criticises Rahal over Irvine Offer to Jordan | work = Atlas F1 | date = 2001-08-28 | publisher = Autosport.com | access-date = 2016-07-04 }}</ref> Ironically, the team fired Irvine little more than a year after firing Rahal, while Newey joined in 2006, a year after the team was sold to Red Bull.\n\nRahal was the interim President and CEO of [[Champ Car|CART]] for six months during the 2000 season.\n\nHis business interests include Bobby Rahal Automotive Group, a network of car dealerships in western and central [[Pennsylvania]] selling [[Acura]], [[BMW]], [[Honda]], [[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar]], [[Land Rover]], [[Lexus]], [[Mercedes-Benz]], [[Toyota]] and [[Volvo]].\n\n==Awards==\n*[[International Motorsports Hall of Fame]] (2004)\n*[[Motorsports Hall of Fame of America]] (2004)<ref name=MSHoF>[http://www.mshf.com/hall-of-fame/inductees/bobby-rahal.html Bobby Rahal] at the [[Motorsports Hall of Fame of America]]</ref>\n*[[SCCA Hall of Fame]] (2013)<ref>{{cite web|last=Lewandowski|first=Dave|title=Notes: Rahal among five elected to SCCA Hall|url=http://www.indycar.com/en/News/2013/01/1-8-Notes-Rahal-elected-to-Hall|publisher=[[IndyCar]]|accessdate=January 9, 2013|date=January 8, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112003517/http://www.indycar.com/en/News/2013/01/1-8-Notes-Rahal-elected-to-Hall|archivedate=January 12, 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Indianapolis Motor Speedway Museum#Auto Racing Hall of Fame|Indianapolis Motor Speedway Hall of Fame]] (2014)\n*[[Simeone Foundation Automotive Museum|Simeone Foundation]] Spirit of Competition Award (2014)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2014/10/28/bobby-rahal-to-receive-simeone-spirit-of-competition-award/|title=Bobby Rahal to receive Simeone Spirit of Competition Award/|website=www.hemmings.com|access-date=2018-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Tribute==\nAt [[WeatherTech Raceway Laguna Seca]], the back straight leading up to the corkscrew was named the \"Rahal Straight\" in his honor.\n\n==Personal life==\nRahal formerly lived in [[New Albany, Ohio]]. Rahal is a graduate of [[Denison University]]. He now lives in Lincoln Park, near the lakefront of Chicago. He is the son of sports car racer Mike Rahal<ref name=aw20120820>{{cite journal|last=Cavin|first=Curt|title=Family Playground: Mid-Ohio is home for the Rahals|journal=[[Autoweek]]|date=August 20, 2012|volume=62|issue=17|pages=60\u201361}}</ref>  and the father of [[Graham Rahal]], who now races in the [[IndyCar Series]].\n\nRahal owns a 1975 [[Lola T360]] which he occasionally races at vintage racing events.\n\nRahal also grew up in the Chicago suburbs and attended [[Glenbard West High School]] as class of 1971.\n\n==Motorsports career results==\n\n===SCCA National Championship Runoffs===\n\n{| class